WEBVTT

00:01.533 --> 00:03.266
Did you know that there
was cannibalism

00:03.333 --> 00:05.667
in Trinidad and Tobago, until 1850?

00:06.300 --> 00:08.133
There were a lot of pirates
in that area, too.

00:08.533 --> 00:10.667
They liked to drag their
prisoners under their ship

00:10.734 --> 00:12.400
across the razor-sharp coral reefs.

00:12.800 --> 00:14.100
<i>-On the other hand...</i>
-[GROANS]

00:14.300 --> 00:15.567
...they invented
barbecued food.

00:16.000 --> 00:17.433
Are you hungry? I am hungry.

00:17.567 --> 00:18.667
Gordo, I'm trying to finish

00:18.734 --> 00:20.500
this article in time
for this week's edition.

00:20.834 --> 00:22.967
"School to schedule
weekly movie night"

00:23.500 --> 00:24.867
Did you know that motion pictures

00:24.934 --> 00:26.333
weren't really invented by Edison,

00:26.400 --> 00:27.400
like everybody thinks?

00:27.467 --> 00:29.266
They were invented
by William Friese-Greene...

00:32.333 --> 00:33.333
...completely deaf.

00:33.400 --> 00:34.834
And, he had eyebrows like,
like out to here.

00:35.000 --> 00:36.000
Gordo!

00:36.367 --> 00:37.767
Sorry. I... I'll zip it.

00:37.934 --> 00:38.934
[SCOFFS]

00:39.066 --> 00:40.500
Wow! They're showing <i>The Mummy? </i>

00:42.066 --> 00:44.266
Fine, Gordo. What'd you need
to tell me about <i>The Mummy?</i>

00:45.100 --> 00:46.667
-That I liked it?
-Is that all?

00:48.633 --> 00:49.967
And, that,
when they made mummies,

00:50.033 --> 00:52.200
they used to pull their organs
out through their nose.

00:52.266 --> 00:53.266
[SCOFFS]

00:55.200 --> 00:56.767
Here's the movie night
story, Mr. Lang.

00:58.500 --> 01:01.100
I feel like I got a real handle
on this journalism stuff.

01:01.734 --> 01:03.333
I think this story lede's a real grabber.

01:05.033 --> 01:06.934
So, for my next story,

01:07.033 --> 01:08.734
I was thinking I
could do the school play.

01:08.867 --> 01:10.600
Mr. Escobar,
the drama teacher, wrote it.

01:12.967 --> 01:15.033
My best friend
Miranda's auditioning for it.

01:15.200 --> 01:16.467
She'll probably
just get a small part.

01:18.133 --> 01:19.133
So, I think I can cover that

01:19.200 --> 01:21.000
all the way from
auditions to opening night.

01:21.166 --> 01:22.166
Bermuda!

01:23.333 --> 01:25.166
I, um, beg your pardon?

01:25.467 --> 01:27.667
Seven letter word
for putting surface.

01:27.734 --> 01:28.734
[CHUCKLES NERVOUSLY]

01:29.333 --> 01:31.734
I think Mr. Lang is
way over journalism.

01:31.834 --> 01:33.667
It seems like he'd rather
be somewhere else.

01:39.100 --> 01:41.166
So, I'll do the story
on the play, then.

01:42.867 --> 01:44.700
And, I'll have it for you
after opening night.

01:46.266 --> 01:48.033
There'll be, uh, reviews,

01:48.100 --> 01:49.934
uh, details
on the production...

01:50.700 --> 01:53.066
Well, it'll just
be all about the play.

01:54.166 --> 01:56.400
Gordo? A little help here.

01:56.767 --> 01:57.967
Well, apparently, the Egyptians

01:58.033 --> 02:00.400
had this wooden hook
that went right into the nose.

02:00.967 --> 02:01.967
[SIGHS]

02:02.834 --> 02:04.834
[THEME SONG PLAYING]

02:44.667 --> 02:46.300
GORDO: You know, when you
become a famous reporter,

02:46.533 --> 02:48.734
I can come along,
and take all the pictures.

02:48.900 --> 02:51.433
Photographers get to wear
stuff with lots of pockets.

02:52.767 --> 02:53.767
I like that.

02:53.934 --> 02:55.734
I don't think you'll be
my photographer, Gordo.

02:55.934 --> 02:58.033
I don't plan on doing
any lingerie fashion shows

02:58.100 --> 02:59.266
or swimsuit competitions.

02:59.633 --> 03:00.800
Well, forget it, then.

03:01.166 --> 03:02.834
-Oh, my gosh! Oh!
-[GRUNTS]

03:05.233 --> 03:06.934
-[GRUNTS]
-Oh, I'm sorry, Tudgeman.

03:07.133 --> 03:08.266
[STAMMERS] I got it!

03:08.400 --> 03:10.400
I didn't even try to, but I... I got it!

03:10.467 --> 03:11.500
What'd you get?
What'd you get?

03:11.567 --> 03:12.567
The lead in the play.

03:12.633 --> 03:14.600
I am gonna be the star
of the school play!

03:14.667 --> 03:16.734
Oh, that is so awesome!
Congratulations!

03:16.800 --> 03:18.200
I thought I'd get in the chorus

03:18.266 --> 03:20.200
or-or paint
the scenery or something.

03:20.300 --> 03:22.100
But no,
I got the biggest part!

03:22.233 --> 03:23.400
That is so great!

03:23.467 --> 03:24.700
I didn't know you were
such a good actress.

03:25.233 --> 03:27.400
To be honest, I didn't
have any real competition.

03:27.467 --> 03:28.867
Mr. Escobar
wrote the play himself.

03:28.934 --> 03:30.166
And it's set in the 1950s,

03:30.266 --> 03:32.233
which is like, a million years ago.

03:32.400 --> 03:34.166
And, none of the regular
drama kids wanna do it.

03:34.300 --> 03:36.767
They all wanna do something
where they were supermodels

03:36.834 --> 03:38.467
and NBA stars who turn to

03:38.867 --> 03:40.633
crime-fighting, rapping robots.

03:40.700 --> 03:42.266
Now, that's a great idea.

03:43.834 --> 03:45.433
But, still,
you're the star of the play.

03:45.500 --> 03:46.700
You got the biggest part!

03:47.233 --> 03:49.000
None of us have
ever been in a play before.

03:49.066 --> 03:51.500
I have. In the third grade
grammar pageant.

03:52.000 --> 03:53.233
I played the question mark.

03:57.600 --> 03:59.633
Gordo, that might
not help you get dates.

04:00.033 --> 04:01.767
Okay, but,
if you guys ever need help

04:01.834 --> 04:03.467
looking confused, inquisitive...

04:05.266 --> 04:08.033
or questioning, I'm your guy.

04:10.200 --> 04:11.300
[SCOFFS]

04:21.533 --> 04:22.533
Hey, Matt.

04:22.800 --> 04:25.200
Lanny. How are you doing?
Whatcha been up to?

04:26.700 --> 04:27.734
Why do you bother?

04:27.800 --> 04:29.266
You know he's not
going to say anything.

04:29.333 --> 04:30.867
I'm gonna get
something out of him, watch.

04:31.200 --> 04:32.867
So, Lanny, you wanna
stick around for dinner?

04:32.934 --> 04:34.467
'Cause, we're having
Gammy McGuire's spareribs.

04:36.066 --> 04:38.700
He can't. He has church choir
practice tonight.

04:39.066 --> 04:42.367
Besides, ribs give
Lanny nightmares.

04:43.533 --> 04:44.934
The walrus dream, right?

04:48.033 --> 04:49.033
Right.

04:49.567 --> 04:52.467
Hey, Mom can I
have $3000 for a jet-ski?

04:53.066 --> 04:54.066
Well, no.

04:54.166 --> 04:56.867
Can I have $1000
for an electronic keyboard?

04:56.934 --> 04:58.066
I don't think so.

04:58.200 --> 04:59.200
MATT: All right.

04:59.266 --> 05:03.066
I guess I'll just settle
for $90 for walkie-talkies.

05:04.700 --> 05:07.000
Matt, we are
not giving you $90.

05:07.567 --> 05:08.900
See, Lanny, I told you

05:08.967 --> 05:11.467
they wouldn't fall for the
start high, go low thing.

05:12.133 --> 05:14.033
What do you need
walkie-talkies for, anyway?

05:14.266 --> 05:16.500
So me and Lanny can
talk to each other at night,

05:16.567 --> 05:18.700
and when we're on our way
to school and stuff.

05:20.000 --> 05:21.433
You know, your mom and I

05:21.500 --> 05:23.266
aren't here just
to give you money, Matt.

05:23.567 --> 05:26.000
I know you're not just here
to give me money.

05:26.834 --> 05:28.166
You have to cook
and wash my clothes

05:28.233 --> 05:29.533
and do all that stuff, too.

05:30.233 --> 05:32.000
What your father
is trying to say is

05:32.066 --> 05:33.767
that we work hard
for our money.

05:33.867 --> 05:35.433
So, if you
want expensive things,

05:35.500 --> 05:37.133
-you gotta earn 'em.
-SAM: That's right, sport.

05:37.300 --> 05:38.533
You want those walkie-talkies,

05:38.600 --> 05:40.333
you're just gonna have to get out there
and earn the money yourself.

05:40.800 --> 05:41.800
Why?

05:43.166 --> 05:44.567
MATT: Earn it yourself?

05:45.000 --> 05:46.567
Where'd they come up
with this stuff?

05:46.734 --> 05:48.600
I mean, it's just so weird.

05:50.867 --> 05:54.033
Okay, a nickel, two pennies,

05:54.367 --> 05:56.500
a peppermint candy,
and a bunch of nuts.

05:57.066 --> 05:59.200
-[NUTS CLATTER]
-I don't know what that is.

06:00.100 --> 06:04.000
And, I think this is the turtle
I lost three years ago.

06:06.567 --> 06:07.567
Well, come on.

06:07.633 --> 06:10.033
We better go start checking
pay phones for change.

06:11.300 --> 06:12.400
Okay. Places, everyone.

06:12.667 --> 06:14.033
LIZZIE: After rehearsal, I'm gonna ask

06:14.100 --> 06:15.400
Mr. Escobar a few questions.

06:15.800 --> 06:16.900
How the play got started,

06:16.967 --> 06:18.400
how he got the ideas
for the show...

06:18.467 --> 06:20.467
What's up with that blue scarf
he always wears?

06:22.300 --> 06:23.734
-[SHUSHES]
-TRAVIS: Listen, Rhonda.

06:23.967 --> 06:25.266
I gotta get out of this town.

06:25.934 --> 06:28.700
My old man,
he just doesn't understand.

06:30.233 --> 06:34.767
Oh, Reb.
Be strong for both of us.

06:35.533 --> 06:38.200
Rhonda walks to the table...

06:41.233 --> 06:42.233
...worried.

06:42.300 --> 06:43.867
All right, okay,
hold on a second, Miranda.

06:43.934 --> 06:45.633
That was great.

06:46.166 --> 06:48.000
Uh, we're on our way
to the stars.

06:48.266 --> 06:50.600
But, "Rhonda walks
to the table worried"

06:50.900 --> 06:53.433
it isn't dialogue,
you actually do it.

06:53.967 --> 06:54.967
It's...

06:57.033 --> 07:00.000
Oh, Reb, be strong
for the both of us.

07:00.867 --> 07:02.734
And, you walk
to the table, worried.

07:03.233 --> 07:04.400
Uh, but,
you don't have to say it.

07:04.567 --> 07:07.333
[CLEARS THROAT] Oh, right,
right. Uh, Mr. Escobar,

07:07.400 --> 07:08.400
I just wanna thank you again,

07:08.467 --> 07:09.600
for letting me
be in this play.

07:09.800 --> 07:11.867
A-acting is, like, the greatest thing I've ever done.

07:14.233 --> 07:17.033
Wow, Miranda's officially
in love with acting.

07:17.700 --> 07:19.100
Maybe,
when she's 30-years-old,

07:19.166 --> 07:20.967
she can play a teenager
on <i>Dawson's Creek.</i>

07:21.200 --> 07:22.367
You're very welcome, Miranda.

07:22.433 --> 07:25.066
Let's move on to the drag
race scene, shall we?

07:25.700 --> 07:27.033
Larry!

07:28.266 --> 07:29.266
Care to join us?

07:30.834 --> 07:32.567
[LAUGHS] It's Tudgeman!

07:32.967 --> 07:36.967
Oh, Stingo, why does Reb
do such dangerous things?

07:37.400 --> 07:39.066
You're his best friend,

07:39.133 --> 07:40.767
and I can't get
through to him!

07:41.166 --> 07:43.400
Why, oh, why
won't he let me in?

07:43.633 --> 07:45.166
How come this is so lame?

07:46.033 --> 07:47.300
It's just rehearsal.

07:47.467 --> 07:49.633
I mean, I'm sure the movie
with the hockey-playing chimp

07:49.700 --> 07:51.567
wasn't brilliant the first time
hey ran through it.

07:52.667 --> 07:53.667
It'll get better.

07:55.166 --> 07:56.400
Yeah, right.

07:57.467 --> 08:00.533
Can't you talk some
sense into him, Tudgeman?

08:01.066 --> 08:02.800
Um, I'm Stingo, remember?

08:03.000 --> 08:06.967
Oh, can't you talk some
sense into him, Stingo?

08:07.900 --> 08:09.734
At least, I sure
hope it gets better.

08:10.867 --> 08:13.967
I can't believe that
garage sale your parents had.

08:14.367 --> 08:17.633
I never knew people would
pay money for old junk.

08:18.433 --> 08:19.467
I mean, that lady, with that

08:19.533 --> 08:21.300
weird purple thing on her neck,

08:21.500 --> 08:25.133
paid five dollars for a cookie
jar shaped like an elf!

08:26.166 --> 08:27.166
[SIGHS]

08:41.900 --> 08:46.700
Hey, I think I'm thinking
what you're thinking.

08:47.533 --> 08:48.700
Sell my stuff.

08:49.100 --> 08:51.367
I've got a room full of junk
I could get rid of!

08:52.300 --> 08:56.066
Then, we'll have the money
for the walkie-talkies.

08:59.500 --> 09:00.834
Here's to money!

09:06.567 --> 09:08.767
Oh, sorry, Lanny, my bad. Here.

09:20.767 --> 09:21.767
Miranda.

09:22.233 --> 09:25.266
Hey! Oh, uh,
I don't have much time.

09:25.333 --> 09:27.900
Mr. Escobar makes us
meditate before we go on.

09:28.400 --> 09:30.734
[CHUCKLES] That outfit is so excellent.

09:30.867 --> 09:32.400
Thanks. I'm gonna be a star!

09:32.467 --> 09:33.500
And I'm gonna write about it!

09:33.567 --> 09:34.767
-[CHUCKLES]
-Here.

09:35.700 --> 09:36.867
It's Cindy Loo-Moo.

09:36.967 --> 09:38.967
Yeah, you gave her to me
before soccer playoffs,

09:39.133 --> 09:40.333
and it helped me score a goal.

09:40.767 --> 09:42.333
So, now she's gonna
bring you some good luck.

09:44.133 --> 09:45.133
Thanks.

09:45.266 --> 09:46.266
Gather round, kids.

09:47.200 --> 09:48.166
Thanks, I gotta go.

09:48.233 --> 09:49.233
Okay.

09:51.433 --> 09:54.367
-Om.
-STUDENTS: Om.

09:56.934 --> 09:58.000
Is Miranda nervous?

09:58.400 --> 10:00.467
No. I've never
seen her so confident.

10:01.900 --> 10:02.900
Here we go.

10:03.633 --> 10:04.633
Yep.

10:05.400 --> 10:06.400
Here we go.

10:06.767 --> 10:08.900
-[VIDEO GAME NOISES]
-[SNORING]

10:14.600 --> 10:16.967
Hey, Reb, I heard you
got expelled from school.

10:17.300 --> 10:18.600
-Hey, it's Tudgeman!
-TRAVIS: That's right, Stingo.

10:18.700 --> 10:20.433
That lousy
vice president, Mr. Birch

10:20.500 --> 10:22.200
hasn't liked me
since my family's moved west,

10:22.834 --> 10:25.300
and I started here
at Southeast Northfield High.

10:25.367 --> 10:27.333
-[GORDO SCOFFS]
-LARRY: Man, that's a gyp, Reb.

10:27.400 --> 10:28.400
They should have launched him

10:28.467 --> 10:30.600
into orbit instead
of the astronauts, oh!

10:30.900 --> 10:33.233
Oh, Stingo,
you and your wisecracks.

10:33.333 --> 10:36.533
Reb! Reb! Ow!

10:37.767 --> 10:39.533
Now, that you've
been expelled,

10:40.333 --> 10:42.900
my father will never
let me see you again.

10:43.266 --> 10:45.266
I'll be re-stick-ted, stricted.

10:45.333 --> 10:46.734
I-I'll be restricted!

10:47.300 --> 10:48.300
My bad.

10:48.633 --> 10:52.934
Um, and senior prom
is two weeks away!

10:53.000 --> 10:54.300
[CLATTERING]

10:57.300 --> 10:58.934
MIRANDA: Reb! Reb!

10:59.000 --> 11:00.033
-[VIDEO GAME NOISES]
-[SNORING]

11:00.100 --> 11:01.500
MIRANDA:
How could you do that, Daddy?

11:01.867 --> 11:04.667
You, you'll never understand Reb,
because he's a wild mustang,

11:04.967 --> 11:07.567
running free, as swiftly as the eagle,

11:07.767 --> 11:09.433
on the prairie flying above us.

11:10.266 --> 11:11.934
The wide open space...

11:14.467 --> 11:15.567
[RETCHES]

11:15.967 --> 11:17.333
So, I'm going with Reb.

11:17.633 --> 11:19.600
Even if I have
to drop out of school.

11:19.734 --> 11:21.367
Guess, now I'll never be...

11:22.300 --> 11:24.433
be, be...

11:27.266 --> 11:28.467
"Valedictorian"

11:32.100 --> 11:33.433
Wait for me, Reb!

11:41.233 --> 11:42.233
Didn't get any better.

11:44.300 --> 11:46.600
It's official. Miranda stinks.

11:57.100 --> 11:58.667
Be careful with that box, Lanny.

11:59.133 --> 12:01.600
I got a Celine Dion
snow globe in there.

12:01.734 --> 12:04.533
That's got to be worth at least
five bucks to some yokel.

12:05.300 --> 12:06.900
No, Lanny, I told you.

12:07.400 --> 12:08.900
First, we're selling the books.

12:09.233 --> 12:11.000
Then the toys, then the clothes.

12:11.734 --> 12:13.133
And, then we'll sell the wagon.

12:13.734 --> 12:14.900
Okay, you ready, Lanny?

12:15.333 --> 12:17.200
Hey, Matt, Lanny.

12:17.734 --> 12:19.000
Uh, is your sister here?

12:19.200 --> 12:20.233
She's inside.

12:20.633 --> 12:23.400
Hey! We're selling
some of my old stuff.

12:24.600 --> 12:25.600
Wanna buy anything?

12:26.033 --> 12:27.367
Uh, I don't think so.

12:30.734 --> 12:32.000
Okay, okay, I can do this.

12:32.066 --> 12:33.200
I've got words in my head.

12:33.867 --> 12:36.100
Come on, words, out
of my head, out, out!

12:36.500 --> 12:37.834
Ooh, Scranton.

12:38.600 --> 12:39.934
That's a city in Pennsylvania.

12:40.367 --> 12:41.734
What stinking good does that do me?

12:42.900 --> 12:43.900
Hey, whatcha doing?

12:44.300 --> 12:45.633
Hmm, the play review.

12:46.567 --> 12:47.567
What's that?

12:48.166 --> 12:49.166
Whee-lo.

12:49.367 --> 12:51.600
[CHUCKLES] It
doesn't have a wheel.

12:52.033 --> 12:53.100
Yeah, I know.

12:53.266 --> 12:55.667
That Lanny, he could
sell ice to a polar bear.

12:59.166 --> 13:00.166
So, how's the review coming?

13:00.567 --> 13:02.967
Mm, great. Just great.

13:04.433 --> 13:07.667
" <i>Greasier</i> Review,
by Lizzie McGuire. Scranton"

13:08.667 --> 13:10.967
Well, I-I-I,
that really says it all.

13:11.133 --> 13:12.734
I probably would've
gone with Pittsburgh,

13:12.800 --> 13:15.100
but you know me.
I overstate things.

13:15.734 --> 13:16.900
That's just doodling.

13:17.800 --> 13:19.533
I can't bring
myself to say that

13:19.900 --> 13:23.000
-Miranda...
-Stinks like a cab driver's armpit?

13:24.533 --> 13:26.633
Gordo, I can't say that.
She's my best friend.

13:26.700 --> 13:28.300
I can't give her a bad review.

13:28.567 --> 13:29.567
It's not a big deal.

13:29.800 --> 13:30.800
Miranda's an actress.

13:30.867 --> 13:32.967
She knows that, sometimes,
you don't get good reviews.

13:33.233 --> 13:35.133
Well, she's counting on me
to support her.

13:35.867 --> 13:38.233
She may be
the worst actress in history,

13:38.533 --> 13:39.633
and you're reporting on it.

13:40.233 --> 13:41.467
You have to report the truth.

13:42.266 --> 13:44.266
Well, I might have
to report the truth,

13:44.467 --> 13:46.533
but that doesn't mean
I can't go easy on her.

13:50.000 --> 13:51.934
Newcomer Miranda Sanchez

13:52.000 --> 13:53.033
gives her best effort

13:53.100 --> 13:56.567
as Rhonda in the school
production of <i>Greasier.</i>

13:57.033 --> 14:00.100
"Unfortunately, her best
effort comes up short"

14:01.033 --> 14:02.133
Comes up short?

14:02.333 --> 14:04.433
Well, I said
your clothes looked nice.

14:04.967 --> 14:06.333
How could you do this?

14:06.400 --> 14:08.333
You know how
important this play is to me!

14:08.633 --> 14:11.433
-I know, and I...
-I can't believe it.

14:13.133 --> 14:14.533
I thought you
were my best friend.

14:24.900 --> 14:27.166
Hey, Miranda.
I got you some flan.

14:27.266 --> 14:28.600
I know how much you like it.

14:30.700 --> 14:32.734
Hey, don't slide away
from me, Miss Thing.

14:32.834 --> 14:34.233
I'm trying to be
the nice one here.

14:34.567 --> 14:35.834
Come on, Miranda.

14:35.967 --> 14:38.533
I mean, I didn't mean
for the review to hurt you.

14:39.200 --> 14:41.300
Hey, I shouldn't even
have to apologize,

14:41.367 --> 14:43.200
Miss Queen of Stinky Acting.

14:43.600 --> 14:45.100
I was just trying to do my job.

14:45.233 --> 14:46.266
I thought that you would understand.

14:46.800 --> 14:48.700
Oh, I-I understand.

14:48.767 --> 14:50.700
I-I understand that
you're just jealous,

14:50.800 --> 14:52.400
that I'm the star of the school play,

14:52.467 --> 14:54.500
and you are just a little reporter!

14:54.900 --> 14:57.934
And, if you think, uh, tearing me down
makes you bigger than me,

14:58.400 --> 14:59.400
well, you're wrong!

14:59.567 --> 15:01.800
Oh, you're a lousy friend!

15:03.000 --> 15:04.433
Well, you're a lousy friend, too,

15:04.500 --> 15:06.000
and a stinkbag actress!

15:06.400 --> 15:07.800
Well, you're a lousy friend, too,

15:07.867 --> 15:09.333
and a stinkbag actress!

15:09.934 --> 15:10.934
Impressive.

15:11.133 --> 15:12.133
[GASPS]

15:12.300 --> 15:13.333
[FRIES SQUELCH]

15:14.233 --> 15:15.233
[SIGHS]

15:16.934 --> 15:17.967
Didn't go so well, huh?

15:18.600 --> 15:20.300
Oh! Those are my fries!

15:20.700 --> 15:22.734
[SIGHS] Brilliant
observation, Gordo.

15:23.533 --> 15:24.800
Miranda, wait up.

15:25.433 --> 15:27.300
Don't even try
to defend Lizzie, Gordo.

15:27.633 --> 15:28.633
I don't have to.

15:28.967 --> 15:30.333
This is a tape
of your performance,

15:30.400 --> 15:32.066
and this is
the review Lizzie wrote.

15:32.600 --> 15:34.066
Take a good look at 'em both.

15:37.633 --> 15:41.000
MIRANDA: <i>Oh, Reb,</i>
<i>I've found you at last.</i>

15:41.333 --> 15:44.133
<i>Don't move. I'm coming</i>
<i>across this arcade and...</i>

15:44.333 --> 15:46.200
[CLATTERING]

15:46.500 --> 15:49.667
<i>Oops. Ow!</i>

15:49.734 --> 15:52.600
<i>And, jumping into your arms</i>
<i>and never letting go!</i>

15:52.867 --> 15:54.033
[TRAVIS YELPS]

15:54.867 --> 15:55.800
<i>Sorry.</i>

15:56.033 --> 15:57.233
MATT: Roger that, Lanny.

15:57.300 --> 15:59.834
I'm exiting the kitchen,
and heading upstairs.

16:00.133 --> 16:02.200
We'll establish
communications from there.

16:02.533 --> 16:03.934
Matt, over and out.

16:04.000 --> 16:05.000
[STATIC BUZZES]

16:05.633 --> 16:07.633
Honey? Honey.

16:08.233 --> 16:09.700
Where did you
get the walkie-talkies?

16:10.000 --> 16:11.333
I earned them, like you said.

16:11.900 --> 16:13.033
Well, I gotta go.

16:13.233 --> 16:14.333
Lanny got his stomach pumped,

16:14.400 --> 16:15.934
and he's gonna
tell me all about it.

16:16.500 --> 16:18.000
How did he earn all that money?

16:18.500 --> 16:19.767
And, what did Lanny eat?

16:21.734 --> 16:24.800
So, even though they
look like marshmallows,

16:25.166 --> 16:27.433
they don't really taste
like marshmallows?

16:28.500 --> 16:29.800
That's good to know.

16:31.100 --> 16:33.066
Well, Matt, over and out.

16:33.367 --> 16:34.400
Talk to you later.

16:35.400 --> 16:36.400
Hey, Matt.

16:43.533 --> 16:45.100
What happened
to all your things, honey?

16:45.166 --> 16:46.333
Sold them.

16:46.400 --> 16:47.834
And, you used the money
for your walkie-talkie?

16:48.200 --> 16:49.300
Uh, yeah.

16:50.333 --> 16:52.967
Well, I gotta go downstairs
and do my spelling homework.

16:53.400 --> 16:54.400
Oh, yeah,

16:54.734 --> 16:57.033
I don't have anything
to wear tomorrow to school.

16:58.800 --> 16:59.800
See ya.

17:01.800 --> 17:04.033
What's it gonna cost
to replace all his stuff?

17:05.400 --> 17:07.600
-Uh...
-Uh, right.

17:07.667 --> 17:08.667
Yeah.

17:09.100 --> 17:10.834
Let's not teach him
anything else for a while.

17:10.900 --> 17:11.934
-Okay?
-Okay.

17:12.834 --> 17:15.533
Hey, Mom. I think I'm gonna
buy my lunch at school tomorrow,

17:15.633 --> 17:16.767
so you don't have to pack me one.

17:17.600 --> 17:18.700
Honey, this isn't for you.

17:18.767 --> 17:20.467
This is for your dad's softball game.

17:20.834 --> 17:23.300
[SCOFFS] You're going
to Dad's softball game?

17:23.567 --> 17:25.734
-Mmm-hmm.
-But, he hardly even gets to play.

17:25.800 --> 17:27.200
And, the only time
he gets on the base,

17:27.266 --> 17:28.500
is when he gets hit by a pitch.

17:33.066 --> 17:34.934
Well, his team finally made it

17:34.967 --> 17:38.400
to the semi-quarter
consolation game, whatever,

17:38.467 --> 17:39.734
and it's the best
they've ever done,

17:39.800 --> 17:41.233
so I figured, what the heck.

17:41.300 --> 17:42.567
But, you don't even like softball.

17:42.900 --> 17:44.367
Honey, it's not
that I don't like it.

17:44.600 --> 17:47.600
I hate it. It's very,
very dull to watch,

17:47.667 --> 17:49.800
and the bleachers are
incredibly uncomfortable.

17:50.667 --> 17:52.233
-Go! Go!
-Y-Go!

17:52.300 --> 17:54.166
-Yeah! Yeah!
-Yeah!

17:54.233 --> 17:55.233
Whoo!

17:56.300 --> 17:58.233
Well, he didn't go
to your blood drive.

17:58.433 --> 18:01.200
Well, to be fair,
he was working that day.

18:01.266 --> 18:02.600
I thought he just didn't wanna go.

18:02.900 --> 18:05.700
Well, if he did,
I would still go to his game.

18:05.900 --> 18:07.400
It's not about who owes who what.

18:07.567 --> 18:09.200
If you love someone,
you support them.

18:10.934 --> 18:12.066
I hate this!

18:12.533 --> 18:14.700
She's showing me how
to be a better friend to Miranda,

18:14.934 --> 18:16.600
and she doesn't even
know she's doing it.

18:17.400 --> 18:18.767
I think Mom might be a witch.

18:19.133 --> 18:21.133
"In spite of the efforts
of the rest of the cast,

18:21.567 --> 18:22.900
"the entire play is dragged down

18:22.967 --> 18:24.900
"by Miranda Sanchez's performance."

18:26.266 --> 18:28.934
You... I...

18:29.867 --> 18:32.300
We were on our way to the stars!

18:34.066 --> 18:35.367
[SIGHS]

18:35.433 --> 18:36.433
Places, everyone.

18:38.000 --> 18:39.100
[SIGHS]

18:39.734 --> 18:42.467
Miranda, I know you think
I'm a terrible friend,

18:42.533 --> 18:44.100
but, before you drop
a spotlight on me,

18:44.467 --> 18:45.834
I wanted to show you this.

18:47.533 --> 18:48.800
It's running in the next issue.

18:49.000 --> 18:50.467
It's a retraction of my review.

18:51.600 --> 18:53.100
"Contrary to previous reports,

18:53.567 --> 18:56.900
"Miranda Sanchez is very entertaining
as Rhonda Dopopopolos."

18:58.467 --> 19:00.867
I was wrong to run a bad review,
and I'm really sorry.

19:01.367 --> 19:03.066
No, you're wrong now.

19:03.934 --> 19:04.934
I was terrible.

19:05.367 --> 19:06.367
You were terrible?

19:06.500 --> 19:08.266
I saw the tape
of my performance.

19:08.767 --> 19:11.200
Ugh! I-I even
wrote a letter to the editor,

19:11.266 --> 19:12.900
saying your review was too nice.

19:13.400 --> 19:15.567
How can you write
a retraction of the truth?

19:15.900 --> 19:17.834
Because, you're my friend.
And you love acting.

19:18.400 --> 19:19.967
I couldn't just
ruin that for you.

19:20.266 --> 19:23.066
Well, thanks, but just
because I'm a bad actress,

19:23.433 --> 19:25.066
doesn't mean you should
be a bad journalist.

19:25.367 --> 19:27.367
Well, if I'd have known I was
gonna make you feel that bad,

19:27.734 --> 19:28.967
I would have never written a review.

19:29.066 --> 19:31.600
Thanks, but if I'd known
I was gonna stink so bad,

19:32.033 --> 19:33.800
I-I would've never
even done the show.

19:36.300 --> 19:37.700
I'm sorry I got mad at you,

19:37.767 --> 19:40.300
but let's face it,
acting is not my thing.

19:40.567 --> 19:41.567
LARRY: Whoo-hoo!

19:41.633 --> 19:43.467
TRAVIS: Oh, Stingo,
you and your wisecracks.

19:43.567 --> 19:44.600
[TRAVIS CHUCKLES]

19:45.000 --> 19:47.000
-Hey, maybe glee club?
-Huh?

19:47.500 --> 19:49.734
Oh, Stingo, you
and your wisecracks.

19:52.033 --> 19:53.900
Glee club.
If I'm a bad actress,

19:54.133 --> 19:55.934
-I have to be a good singer.
-[CHUCKLES]

19:56.533 --> 19:58.100
Glee club? Singing?

19:58.567 --> 19:59.633
Oh, no!

19:59.800 --> 20:02.400
Oh, Stingo,
you and your wisecracks!

20:04.033 --> 20:06.166
Oops. That's my cue.

20:06.233 --> 20:07.233
[CHUCKLES]

20:07.800 --> 20:08.800
Poor audience.

20:09.834 --> 20:11.900
Reb! Reb! Ow!

20:12.000 --> 20:13.333
-[CRASHES]
-Ooh!

20:13.400 --> 20:14.400
[CHUCKLES]

20:14.967 --> 20:16.767
Singing. Just when you think

20:16.834 --> 20:19.100
Miranda's hit bottom,
she gets a shovel.

20:28.333 --> 20:30.467
<i>Look at me</i>

20:30.900 --> 20:35.834
<i>I will never pass</i>
<i>for a perfect bride</i>

20:36.300 --> 20:38.500
<i>Or a perfect daughter</i>

20:39.233 --> 20:41.367
<i>Can it be</i>

20:41.433 --> 20:46.166
<i>I'm not meant to play this part</i>

20:46.767 --> 20:47.800
<i>Now I see...</i>

20:47.867 --> 20:48.967
Hello, Mariah Carey.

20:49.333 --> 20:51.667
She really found something
she doesn't stink at.

20:54.166 --> 20:55.233
Good for Miranda.

20:55.300 --> 20:56.500
I bet, if I keep looking,

20:56.567 --> 20:58.533
I can find a thing
I'm really good at, too.

21:02.500 --> 21:04.633
<i>Somehow</i>

21:04.700 --> 21:09.667
<i>I cannot hide who I am</i>

21:10.100 --> 21:12.533
<i>Though I've tried</i>

21:13.000 --> 21:17.667
<i>When will my reflection show</i>

21:18.166 --> 21:24.266
<i>Who I am inside?</i>

21:27.533 --> 21:28.533
MALE CAMERA CREW: B mark.

21:28.600 --> 21:29.633
I'm your guy.

21:30.667 --> 21:32.333
[LAUGHING]

21:32.633 --> 21:34.166
Brilliant observation, Gordo.

21:36.800 --> 21:38.266
-[LAUGHING]
-[CREW LAUGHING]

21:38.333 --> 21:39.333
-Got it!
-DIRECTOR: Cut.

21:39.633 --> 21:41.600
Hey, don't slide
away from... Ah!

21:42.934 --> 21:43.934
Oops.

21:44.166 --> 21:47.967
<i>Om. Om.</i>

21:49.667 --> 21:51.166
-DIRECTOR: And, cut.
-[ALL LAUGH]

21:51.567 --> 21:52.834
I was just trying to do my job,

21:52.900 --> 21:54.100
I thought you
would understand.

21:54.300 --> 21:57.600
Oh, I-I under...
[CHUCKLING] I understand.

21:58.233 --> 22:00.367
[ALL LAUGHING]

22:02.900 --> 22:04.900
[THEME MUSIC PLAYING]
